### Function Basics

Functions are reusable blocks of code that perform a specific task. Every Dart program has at least the `main()` function.

```dart
// Function that returns a value
int add(int a, int b) {
  return a + b;
}

// Function that returns nothing
void greet(String name) {
  print('Hello, $name!');
}
```

### Function Syntax

```dart
returnType functionName(parameters) {
  // function body
  return value;
}
```

### Calling Functions

```dart
void main() {
  int result = add(5, 3);
  print(result); // 8

  greet('Alice'); // Hello, Alice!
}

int add(int a, int b) => a + b;

void greet(String name) {
  print('Hello, $name!');
}
```

### Arrow Functions

For single-expression functions, use the arrow syntax `=>`:

```dart
int square(int x) => x * x;
bool isEven(int x) => x % 2 == 0;
void printMessage(String msg) => print(msg);
```

### Required Parameters

```dart
void displayInfo(String name, int age) {
  print('$name is $age years old');
}
```

### Return Types

| Return Type | Description |
|-------------|-------------|
| `void` | Returns nothing |
| `int`, `String`, etc. | Returns specific type |
| `dynamic` | Returns any type (avoid) |
| `Future<T>` | Returns async value |

> **Key Point:** Dart functions are objects (instances of `Function`). They can be assigned to variables, passed as arguments, and returned from other functions.

codeExample:
int add(int a, int b) => a + b;
int multiply(int a, int b) => a * b;

void printResult(int Function(int, int) operation, int x, int y) {
  print('Result: ${operation(x, y)}');
}

void main() {
  printResult(add, 5, 3);
  printResult(multiply, 5, 3);
  printResult((a, b) => a - b, 10, 4);
}
